[[Rear Admiral (United States)|Rear Admiral]] '''Thorvald A. Solberg''' (17 February 1894 <U+2013> 16 May 1964) was a senior officer in the [[United States Navy]], and the Chief of the [[Office of Naval Research]] from 1948 to 1951.

==Biography==
Thorvald A. Solberg was born in [[Mason, Wisconsin]], on 17 February 1894,{{sfn|Ancell|Miller|1996|p=615}} the son of Norwegian immigrants Thomas and Martha Solberg.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://interactive.ancestry.com/7602/004120617_00084/73429803 |title=1900 United States Federal Census  for Thorval A Solberg |publisher=Ancestry.com |accessdate=14 February 2014}}</ref> In 1905, the family moved to [[Sandpoint, Idaho]], where he graduated from [[Sandpoint High School]] in 1911.<ref name="obit">{{cite news |title=Admiral Solberg, Former Resident, Called by Death  |date=4 June 1964 |url=http://trees.ancestry.com/tree/26597758/person/1887622420/mediax/2 |accessdate=14 February 2014}}</ref>

Solberg was appointed to the [[United States Naval Academy]] in [[Annapolis, Maryland]] by [[United States Senate|Senator]] [[William Borah]] of Idaho, and was commissioned in the [[United States Navy]] as an [[ensign]] on graduation in 1916.<ref name="obit"/> During [[World War I]] he served on board the [[cruiser]] {{USS|Tacoma|CL-20|6}}.{{sfn|Ancell|Miller|1996|p=615}}

Solberg  studied [[electrical engineering]] at the [[Naval Postgraduate School]],<ref name="obit"/> and then attended [[Columbia University]], receiving a [[Master of Science]] (M.S.) degree in 1924.{{sfn|Ancell|Miller|1996|p=615}} In 1931 and 1932 he worked on the development of a [[boiler]] compound to prevent the build up of [[limescale]] in ships' boilers. This was approved by the [[Bureau of Engineering]] in its 1933 "Standard Navy Boiler Compound Specifications".{{sfn|Carlisle|1998|p=100}}

During [[World War II]], he was an engineering officer on the staff of the Commander, Battle Force from July 1939 to April 1941. He then went to London as a naval observer. He returned to the United States in March 1944, and served with the [[Bureau of Ships]] until October 1946. He was promoted to the rank of [[Rear Admiral (United States)|rear admiral]] in 1945, with his seniority backdated to December 1942.{{sfn|Ancell|Miller|1996|p=615}}

During [[Operation Crossroads]] in 1946, Solberg was responsible for preparing the target fleet.{{sfn|Christman|1998|p=220}} As head of the Bureau of Ships' Research and Standards Branch, he was also appointed to the Military Liaison Committee of the [[United States Atomic Energy Commission|Atomic Energy Commission]] in November 1946.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1893&dat=19461104&id=KK8fAAAAIBAJ&sjid=ItcEAAAAIBAJ&pg=4511,798756 | newspaper=[[The Southeast Missourian]] |title=Army-Navy Group to Work With  Atomic Energy Commission Named |date= 4  November 1946 |accessdate=14 February 2014}}</ref> He became the Chief of the [[Office of Naval Research]] in 1948, a position he held until he retired in 1951.<ref name="obit"/>

Solberg was twice awarded the [[Legion of Merit]].<ref name="obit"/> In 1947, [[Solberg Inlet]] in Antarctica was named after him by the [[Ronne Antarctic Research Expedition]] (RARE) in recognition of the assistance given to the expedition by Solberg and the Office of Naval Research.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://data.aad.gov.au/aadc/gaz/display_name.cfm?gaz_id=111260 |title=Name Details: Solberg Inlet |publisher=Australian Antarctic Data Centre |accessdate=13 February 2013}}</ref>

He was forced to retire in 1951 after reaching 35 years of service.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://archives.aaas.org/golden/pdf/226_19510115.pdf |date=15 January 1951 |title=Conversation with Rear Admiral T. Solberg, Director, Office of Naval Research |last=Golden |first=William T. |authorlink=William T. Golden |publisher= American Association for the Advancement of Science  |accessdate=14 February 2014}}</ref> He died on 16 March 1964,{{sfn|Ancell|Miller|1996|p=615}} and was buried in [[Arlington National Cemetery]].<ref name="FG" >{{Find a Grave | grid = 49319784 | name = Adm Thorvald Arthur Solberg | date = 6 March 2010| accessdate = 14 February 2014 | author     = John C. Anderson }} </ref> He was survived by his wife, his son John B. Solberg, and his stepdaughter Gretchen Mobberley.<ref name="obit"/>

